### Steps to reproduce

So the problem is that if we deviate from the normal structure:

***1
[Email textfield]
[Password textfield]

To something like this:

***2
[Email textfield]
[Password textfield]
[Confirm password textfield]

OR

***3
[Current password textfield]
[Email textfield]
[New password textfield]
[Confirm new password textfield]

The autofill feature in conjunction with AutofillGroup produces very random behaviour for causing the save/update IOS keychain prompt to appear on the screen for passwords. What I mean by random is that the smallest thing can cause the prompt behaviour to either appear on the screen, or most of the time not appear at all! The only time I observed it working 100% of the time was when we had a similar structure to ***1.

Also I am confident that we have the apple site association set-up correctly as well. This was also tested on a real IPhone 15 pro max, IOS version 17.4.1.

1. Copy provided code onto a page.
2. Try inputting textfields and clicking the submit button to see if you can get the IOS keychain save/update password prompt to appear consistently on the screen. The only time I can get it to appear consistently is when I leave my cursor on last textfield and click change password while keyboard is open, or click done on the keyboard when cursor is on the last textfield. 

Including any extra key events or moving cursor is enough to offset this process for me.

### Expected results

What I expect to happen, is the when the change password button is clicked, the save/update password prompt should appear every time. The position of the cursor, or extra key events shouldn't be able to dictate this behaviour

### Actual results

What actually happens is that the IOS keychain prompt to save/update password is very inconsistent. Please refer to the video for examples of what I mean. If I introduce any extra key events than needed, there is a high change this can prevent the actual prompt from showing up at all, when submitting!

